      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a fascinating chemical process, a complex cascade of reactions between amino acids and reducing sugars that gives browned food its distinctive flavor and aroma. It's what makes seared steak taste so much better than boiled steak, and it's what gives toast its wonderful, nutty scent. To really get the flavor profile going, you need to heat things up, and this reaction starts to become noticeable around 285°F (140°C) and really kicks into high gear above 300°F (150°C). Keep in mind that the exact temperature can vary depending on the ingredients, but that's where the magic happens!",
